data.text:
The PID Fifth Avenue Line is a rapid transit line in the B Division of the Potato City Subway. Opening in 1933, it was the Potato Independent Subway System's first line running the core of Potatoburg, and has gradually expanded towards northern Cadland – today, it spans 13 stations including three elevated between Jamaica and Halson Yards.

Extent and Service[]

The following service serve part or all of the Fifth Avenue Line. The trunk line color is blue:

Time period Section of line All Times Herald Square to 57th Street Weekdays South of 57th Street All Times Except Late Nights Entire Line All Times

The Fifth Avenue Line begins at Union Turnpike in Cocoa Heights as a 2 track Line in Cadland, with unused side tracks being visible at 77th Street-World Trade Center. The line goes through the Lincoln Tunnel and into 57th Street, where B and D Trains join the line from the WPT Waterside Boulevard Line on the lower level. Passing the connection to the PID Blokaway Line at 47th Street and the abandoned 42nd Street-Junko Heights station the line continues underground until it reaches 26th Street-Saint Marks Avenue where the line goes elevated until Booth Street where it descends back underground towards Herald Square. Turning west B trains split from Fifth Avenue towards the WPT Second Avenue Line, while the other lines continue towards 10th Street, the final stop before the Halson Tubes where the line continues on the Westpotat on the PID Garcia Avenue Line.

History[]

1933-1953[]

The Fifth Avenue Line was opened on September 15th 1933 by the Potato Independent Subway, with major help from the Westpotat Potatoburg Transit company, running from Ninth Street-Tsukino Pier (Currently 10th Street) in Potatoburg to 77th Street-Cadland Financial in Cadland, which would later be extended to 80th Street-Museum of Heartie History on October 10th 1935. On May 13th 1936 the Waterside Boulevard Line would open by the WPT, extending B and D Trains from 57th Street to 76th Street.

Portland Street would open on June 22, 1940 as a extra infill station, however structural issues and low ridership caused the station to close on May 30th, 1949.

On September 1, 1953, the 42nd Street station closed due to the short distance between it and it's surrounding stations, and during the same year EE(K) Trains would end rush hour short turns at 57th Street.

On August 30, 1960, the 77th Street-Cadland Financial station would close for rebuilds until September 6, 1971.

On December 11, 1972, the 94th Street-Union Turnpike station(Now simply Union Turnpike) opened, being the final extension of the Fifth Avenue Line with the addition of 97th Street Yard.

On September 23, 1978, the LGA Express would begin service, running from Alberta Turnpike to 47th Street.

In 1979 77th Street would be renamed to 77th Street-World Trade Center, and in 1997 Union Turnpike would get renamed with the 94th Street name being taken away.

On April 12, 1992, the LGA Express discontinued service due to budget cuts and increasing redundancy.

On June 30, 2004, a major fire occurred at the South 10th Street station. While no fatalities were suffered, the station suffered major damage and had to close for repairs. The station would eventually reopen on July 12, 2007.
